ns, resolves\napprovals, and can set up and start a runner on the local machine."],[420,"The `start`/`complete`/`fail`/event-append and artifact-upload endpoints under `/api/runs/{id}` are the runner protocol (runner-scoped tokens, run ownership enforced) — see Runners."],[1238,"The agent's output failed schema validation."],[127,"The API exposes these as `whatHappensIfApproved` / `whatHappensIfRejected` / `whatHappensIfChangesRequested` / `whatHappensIfIgnored` in each card's `context`, alongside the ask, the linked run, and deep links."],[192,"The API hands these links back so agents and integrations can point humans at the right screen without building URLs themselves:"],[655,"The API-first guarantee"],[90,"The ask contract"],[991,"The bootstrap script installs these for you, retargeted to your install\ndirectory, env-file location, and node binary. Secrets live in the\n`EnvironmentFile`s (mode `0600`), never in the units."],[901,"The bot's API token."],[219,"The caller selects profiles per run with `input.postRunHooks: [\"publish-docs\", …]`."],[323,"The caller's execution intent: `executionMode: \"local\" | \"remote\" | \"auto\"` (optionally a specific `runnerLocation`). `remote` targets the shared remote/VPS pool (default location `vps`); `auto` takes any matching runner."],[252,"The catalog"],[574,"The catalog unit of Runyard - versioned definitions with schemas, immutable source bundles, and portable packages."],[929,"The CLI stores named remotes (Hub URL + token) in `~/.runyard/config.json`\n(mode `0600`). Every command accepts global options `--url`, `--token`,\n`--remote <name>`, and `--json` (machine-readable output)."],[672,"The complete MCP tool set (parity-tested against the API surface). Connect with `runyard mcp install` or the `runyard-mcp` stdio server."],[1309,"The corresponding MCP tools are `get_workflow_source`, `list_workflow_bundles`, and `get_workflow_bundle` (which does include the source). You can also publish a bundle directly with `POST /api/workflow-bundles` / `publish_workflow_bundle` and reference it by `workflow.bundleId`, but prefer inline source — the Hub publishes the bundle for you."],[106,"The creator of a card states the ask up front, and every surface renders it verbatim:"],[1067,"The current saved remote"],[879,"The decision is applied to the paused workflow on the runner and it resumes past the gate."],[468,"The encrypted secret store - admin-managed, listable by name only, delivered to runs at claim time and never returned by the API."],[927,"The fastest path is the install script served by your own Hub, which downloads\nthe CLI tarball from the same instance (`/cli.tgz`), installs `runyard` and\n`runyard-mcp` into `~/.local/bin`, and logs you in:"],[669,"The full HTTP surface, generated from the Hub's API surface registry — it cannot drift from the routes the server actually registers."],[887,"The gated side effect is allowed to run."],[1123,"The GitHub Actions pipeline (`.github/workflows/release.yml` and `images.yml`) has four jobs:"],[875,"The held run is released to the queue and executes."],[234,"The hook did not run."],[896,"The Hub can post approval cards to a Telegram chat and accept decisions from the buttons on them."],[1006,"The Hub is a single HTTP listener; any TLS-terminating proxy that forwards **all\npaths** to the Hub port works. With Caddy:"],[987,"The Hub listens on `127.0.0.1:43117` by default. Start a runner in a second\nprocess:"],[977,"The Hub uses the built-in `node:sqlite` module (started with `--experimental-sqlite`)"],[675,"The live, private catalog: workflows with schemas, execution modes, runner pool state, and ready-to-use CLI/MCP invocations."],[309,"The machines that claim and execute runs via the Smithers engine - registration, tags, capacity, health, and sandboxing."],[1057,"The parity guarantee"],[999,"The portable base stack is `docker-compose.yml` at the repo root:"],[431,"The preview returns a human-readable description plus the next fire instants — nothing is created."],[230,"The profile cannot execute — typically missing named secrets or a disabled secret store."],[232,"The profile was not eligible for this run."],[1119,"The release-train helper"],[983,"The repository ships a one-command, idempotent bootstrap script for a fresh\nLinux box:"],[989,"The repository ships generic units in `deploy/`. The Hub unit\n(`deploy/runyard.service`):"],[21,"The repository's install script is a one-command, idempotent bootstrap. It installs Node 22 and pnpm if needed, clones Runyard at the latest release tag (default `/opt/runyard`), generates an env file with a `SECRETS_ENC_KEY` and session secret, creates the data directory, and installs systemd units for the Hub and a runner:"],[1195,"The reusable secret store is enabled by setting `SECRETS_ENC_KEY` (a 32-byte key) on the Hub; without a valid key the feature is disabled rather than degraded. Values are encrypted at rest and are write-only from the API's point of view: `GET /api/secrets` returns names and metadata, never values, and secrets are redacted from API responses, events, approval cards, and audit entries. Workflows reference secrets by name; the Hub injects values into runs that declared them."],[1235,"The run exceeded a deadline or an operation timed out."],[476,"the run input's `input.secretNames` list."],[877,"The run is cancelled — a human \"no\" is a decision, not a failure."],[876,"The run is cancelled; your note tells the requester what to change."],[1220,"The run is held on an approval card, which is by design: approval-held runs are never failed or reaped for waiting. Find and resolve the card — web **Approvals**, `runyard approvals` then `runyard approve|reject|request-changes <approval-id>`, or the MCP tools. See Approvals."],[347,"The run lifecycle, preflight and run drafts, events and artifacts, reruns, and promotion."],[988,"The runner authenticates with a runner-scoped token (`RUNYARD_HUB_TOKEN`); on a\nfresh Hub it may use the bootstrap token until you mint one."],[288,"The runner observes the terminal status on its next poll and cancels the detached engine run, and the gateway refuses further calls from that run's token (`403`)."],[345,"The runner protocol endpoints intentionally have no MCP tools — they are Hub↔runner machinery, not an operator surface."],[709,"The runner protocol: register, heartbeat, claim runs, report lifecycle events and artifacts"],[514,"The runner protocol: register, heartbeat, claim runs, report lifecycle, upload artifacts."],[1189,"The runner protocol: register, heartbeat, claim runs, report lifecycle."],[1229,"The runner's preflight refused to execute (missing workflow source, auth not ready, repo path problems)."],[36,"The same data lives at `GET /api/runs/{id}`, `/api/runs/{id}/timeline`, `/api/runs/{id}/logs`, and `/api/runs/{id}/artifacts`, and in the web run page — the Hub is the source of truth even when execution happened on a local runner."],[510,"The same operating surface for MCP clients."],[1187,"The same operations over the MCP server."],[705,"The same operations, issued for MCP clients"],[23,"The script never prints secrets, never applies updates automatically, and prints a Caddy reverse-proxy snippet if you want TLS in front (recommended for anything non-local — see the security guide)."],[1069,"The server exposes **87 tools**, generated from the same API surface registry\nthe Hub's routes and `/openapi.json` come from. Grouped by resource:"],[1064,"The server name is `runyard` for the default remote and `runyard-<remote>` for\nothers, so one client can talk to several Hubs. &#x2A;*No token is stored in client\nconfigs.** At startup the server resolves its target in this order:"],[41,"The shared catalog of reusable agent roles, skills, and knowledge resources that workflows reference."],[186,"The shared catalogs (append `/:slug` for one entry)."],[226,"The side effect completed."],[889,"The side effect is skipped; the run's completed work is unaffected."],[888,"The side effect is skipped; your note explains what to change."],[228,"The side effect itself failed."],[1304,"The source is a small Smithers TSX workflow (modeled on the seeded `hello` workflow): one task, structured output validated with Zod."],[42,"The three catalogs"],[1068,"The token's scopes decide what the tools may do — a token with `mcp` scope can\ndiscover, preflight, and run workflows; `admin` unlocks the admin tools listed\nbelow."],[1110,"The tool list, the HTTP routes, and `/openapi.json` are all generated from one\nregistry, and a test fails the build when they drift: **every Hub API operation\nis either exposed as an MCP tool or carries a documented exemption** (exempt\noperations are browser pages, install assets, the runner-to-Hub machine\nprotocol, SSE streams that tools cover by polling, and legacy aliases). If you\ncan do it in the web UI or over HTTP, your agent can do it over MCP."],[1056,"The tool surface"],[690,"The typical flow"],[541,"The web app is an ordinary API client. `POST /api/auth/token-login` exchanges an access token for a **session cookie** — a signed copy of the token — so the browser session carries *exactly* the token's scopes, no extra power. Admin sections of the web app appear only for admin-scoped sessions. `POST /api/auth/logout` clears the cookie."],[677,"The web app is an ordinary client of the same HTTP API, with no privileged endpoints. Every route is declared in one registry that also generates `openapi.json` and is parity-tested against the MCP tool list — so a lossless third-party client is possible by construction: anything the web app can show or do, your client can too, over HTTP or MCP."],[283,"The web app: a usage chip on run cards, usage/budget on run detail, and fleet-wide totals in `GET /api/dashboard` (`stats.usage`)."],[1312,"The web app's workflow create/edit screens are ordinary clients of `POST /api/workflows` and `PATCH /api/workflows/{id}`: they submit the definition with inline source bytes and the Hub publishes the bundle, exactly as above. There is no separate, privileged authoring path."],[1276,"The web editor"],[1244,"The workflow concluded a human must act."],[218,"The workflow must opt in via `workflow.hooks.allowedProfiles` (a list of profile slugs, or `\"*\"`); no opt-in means no hooks, default-closed."],[1301,"The workflow source bytes, sent inline as a string (aliases: `workflow.sourceBytes`, `workflow.code`)."],[475,"the workflow's declared `workflow.secrets` list, and"],[176,"The workflow's runs."],[1061,"Then let the CLI write your AI client's MCP config:"],[1007,"Then set `BASE_URL=https://hub.example.com` in the Hub's env file and restart.\nAn `https://` base URL switches the Hub into production session mode. If the\nproxy is not on loopback, set the trust-proxy configuration accordingly so\nclient IPs (used by rate limiting) are read from `X-Forwarded-For` only when\nthat header is trustworthy."],[952,"Then start the runner against the current remote (it inherits the remote's URL\nand token, or `RUNYARD_HUB_URL` / `RUNYARD_HUB_TOKEN`):"],[20,"This page takes you from a fresh Linux box to a completed workflow run with logs and artifacts in the Hub."],[385,"Three ways to use it:"],[848,"Timed approvals and fallback"],[92,"Timed approvals with fallback"],[1063,"To configure a client by hand, print the snippet instead:"],[30,"To run an ad-hoc runner on any other machine (for example your laptop, for `local` execution):"],[671,"token"],[674,"token"],[548,"Token name and scopes."],[1090,"Tokens"],[494,"Tokens & Scopes"],[699,"Tokens are minted by an admin (web UI, `POST /api/tokens`, or the CLI) and carry\n**scopes**:"],[1181,"Tokens carry scopes; admins mint them from the Connect tab or `POST /api/tokens`."],[922,"Tokens, audit, and catalog"],[1071,"Tools"],[1108,"Tools marked † require an admin-scoped token."],[1125,"Trigger"],[213,"Trigger a preview deploy for a configured project."],[1206,"Troubleshooting"],[1156,"Trust boundary"],[1155,"Trust boundary, token scopes, secrets handling, runner sandboxing, and production posture for a Runyard deployment."],[951,"Turn a machine into a runner in three steps. First scaffold a workspace\n(requires `bun` and the `smithers` engine on `PATH`; it warns if no `claude`,\n`codex`, or `pi` agent CLI is found):"],[1180,"Two narrow exceptions authenticate by other means: `POST /api/telegram/webhook` is verified against the configured bot and webhook secret, and `POST /api/workflow-endpoints/{slug}` submissions authenticate with that endpoint's own secret (below). `GET /api/setup` returns only a reduced identity payload (instance name, auth mode) to unauthenticated callers."],[1247,"Unclassified failure."],[764,"Unified ascending timeline (`since=<iso>`, `limit=<n>`); backs `runyard tail`"],[1265,"Unified timeline: status transitions, events, artifacts as NDJSON."],[925,"Updating a host install"],[1274,"Updating a workflow"],[603,"Updating a workflow bumps its integer `version` and snapshots the previous definition. `GET /api/workflows/{name}/versions` lists the versions observed on past runs, and every run records the `workflowVersion` it executed. Bundle versions count separately, per publish."],[351,"Usage and budgets"],[290,"Usage is captured at the **inference boundary**, through two paths:"],[267,"Usage metering & budgets"],[269,"Usage records and the run aggregate"],[523,"Use for"],[114,"Values"],[898,"Variable"],[1009,"Variable"],[1030,"Variable"],[22,"Verify the Hub is up:"],[1258,"Verify, in order: `TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN` and `TELEGRAM_APPROVAL_CHAT_ID` are set on the Hub; the bot's webhook points at `https://hub.example.com/api/telegram/webhook` with the matching `TELEGRAM_WEBHOOK_SECRET`; the bot is a member of the target chat; and the users pressing buttons are listed in `TELEGRAM_APPROVAL_USER_IDS`. Response-endpoint deliveries record their state (`status`, `attempts`, `last_error`) on `GET /api/runs/{id}` under `responseEndpoints[]`."],[578,"Versioning"],[1116,